      title: "Ultrasound Physics — Sonography Canada Exam Preparation",
      content: "Sonography Canada certifies diagnostic medical sonographers across Canada through a national competency-based certification examination. The physics and instrumentation domain is a core component tested across all Sonography Canada credential categories: Generalist, Cardiac, and Vascular. Sound wave properties are fundamental: frequency (Hz), wavelength (m), period (s), amplitude, and intensity. Diagnostic ultrasound operates between 1 and 20 MHz. The propagation speed in soft tissue is 1540 m/s, and this value is assumed by all ultrasound systems regardless of the actual medium. The relationship between frequency, wavelength, and propagation speed is: wavelength = propagation speed / frequency. Higher frequencies yield shorter wavelengths and better axial resolution but less penetration depth. Acoustic impedance (Z = density × velocity) determines reflection at tissue boundaries. Attenuation combines absorption, reflection, scattering, and refraction, averaging 0.5 dB/cm/MHz in soft tissue. Transducer types include linear array (high frequency, superficial), curvilinear (lower frequency, deeper penetration), phased array (small footprint, cardiac), and endocavitary. Piezoelectric elements convert electrical energy to sound and vice versa. Imaging modes include B-mode (2D brightness), M-mode (motion display), and Doppler modes. The Sonography Canada examination framework emphasizes competency-based assessment aligned with the Canadian National Competency Profile for diagnostic medical sonographers."
