      content: "The Sonography Canada Generalist certification encompasses abdominal sonography as a core competency domain. Canadian sonographers perform abdominal examinations following protocols established by their provincial regulatory bodies and institutional standards. The Canadian healthcare system provides universal access to diagnostic ultrasound, making abdominal sonography one of the most commonly requested examinations. Hepatic assessment evaluates parenchymal echogenicity, vascular anatomy (hepatic veins, portal veins, hepatic arteries), and focal lesions. Normal liver echogenicity is equal to or slightly greater than the renal cortex. Hepatic steatosis is the most common diffuse liver disease encountered, presenting as diffusely increased echogenicity with decreased visualization of the intrahepatic vessels and diaphragm. The gallbladder is examined in the fasting state (minimum 6-8 hours NPO). Cholelithiasis presents as echogenic foci with posterior acoustic shadowing and gravity-dependent movement. Acute cholecystitis demonstrates the combination of gallstones, wall thickening (>3 mm), pericholecystic fluid, and a positive sonographic Murphy sign. The CBD is measured at the porta hepatis; normal is less than 6 mm (up to 8-10 mm post-cholecystectomy). The pancreas is assessed for size, echogenicity, and focal lesions. Renal sonography evaluates cortical echogenicity (normally ≤ liver), dimensions, hydronephrosis, and masses. The SFU (Society for Fetal Urology) grading system is used in Canadian practice for hydronephrosis classification. Splenic dimensions and aortic measurements complete the standard abdominal survey."
