      content: "Musculoskeletal (MSK) ultrasound in Canada is an expanding area of practice for sonographers, radiologists, and increasingly for point-of-care applications by sports medicine physicians, rheumatologists, and physiotherapists. While MSK ultrasound competencies are not currently part of the core Sonography Canada Generalist examination, many Canadian institutions include MSK sonography in advanced practice roles. Canadian MSK ultrasound practice follows guidelines from the Canadian Association of Radiologists, the European Society of Musculoskeletal Radiology (ESSR), and institutional protocols. High-frequency linear transducers (12-18 MHz) provide excellent spatial resolution for superficial musculoskeletal structures. Key examination areas include the rotator cuff (most common indication), Achilles tendon, lateral epicondyle, and carpal tunnel. Anisotropy remains the most significant artifact: tendons appear falsely hypoechoic when the ultrasound beam is not perpendicular to the tendon fibers. Dynamic examination during active and passive motion is a unique advantage over MRI. Canadian sports medicine clinics and rheumatology practices increasingly use MSK ultrasound for both diagnosis and guided interventions. The Canadian Academy of Sport and Exercise Medicine (CASEM) supports MSK ultrasound training for sports medicine physicians. In Canadian radiology practice, MSK ultrasound complements MRI and may be preferred for tendon assessment, dynamic evaluation, and guided procedures."
