      content: "Doppler principles are fundamental to the Sonography Canada certification across all credential categories — Generalist, Cardiac, and Vascular. Canadian sonographers must demonstrate competency in both the physics of Doppler ultrasound and its clinical applications. The Doppler effect describes the frequency shift produced when sound waves interact with moving reflectors (red blood cells). The Doppler equation relates velocity to frequency shift, transmitted frequency, propagation speed, and the cosine of the angle between the beam and flow direction. Angle dependence is critical: accurate velocity measurements require angles less than 60 degrees. At 0 degrees, maximum frequency shift occurs; at 90 degrees, no Doppler shift is detected. Pulsed-wave Doppler provides depth-specific velocity information but is limited by the Nyquist frequency (PRF/2); aliasing occurs when the Doppler shift exceeds this limit. Continuous-wave Doppler measures all velocities along the beam path without aliasing but cannot determine depth. Color flow Doppler maps mean velocity and direction using the BART convention (Blue Away, Red Toward). Power Doppler displays signal amplitude without directional information and is more sensitive to slow flow. In Canadian clinical practice, Doppler is applied across vascular (carotid, peripheral), obstetric (umbilical artery, MCA), and abdominal (hepatic, renal) applications. The resistive index (RI) and pulsatility index (PI) are key hemodynamic parameters used across all specialties. Canadian practice standards emphasize proper technique, angle correction, and quality assurance for Doppler measurements."
